    <div class="page-header">Flood History</div>

    <p>
        Punjab has faced multiple natural and man-made disasters since 1988. These events led to the evolution of a formal, structured disaster management system in the state, culminating in the establishment of SDMA Punjab after the Disaster Management Act, 2005.
    </p>

    <h2>Historical Timeline</h2>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>1988 – Punjab’s Most Devastating Floods</h3>
        <p>
            • One of the worst floods in Punjab history, impacting districts like Jalandhar, Ludhiana, Kapurthala, and Firozpur.<br>
            • Caused massive agricultural loss and drowning of entire villages.<br>
            • 9,000 out of ~12,989 villages flooded; ~34 lakh people affected.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>1993–1995 – Repeated Monsoon Floods</h3>
        <p>
            • Major rise in water levels of Beas, Sutlej, and Ravi rivers.<br>
            • Strengthening of drainage channels and embankments began.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>1998 – Punjab Earthquake Impact</h3>
        <p>
            • Earthquake shocks from HP affected northern Punjab.<br>
            • First introduction of building safety guidelines.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2000 – Waterlogging Crisis</h3>
        <p>
            • Heavy rainfall created prolonged waterlogging in Malwa region.<br>
            • Government launched canal and drainage repair projects.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2003 – Industrial Fires & Chemical Hazards</h3>
        <p>
            • Major industrial fires in Ludhiana & Gobindgarh.<br>
            • Chemical disaster response teams formed.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2005 – SDMA Formation</h3>
        <p>
            • Disaster Management Act passed nationwide.<br>
            • Punjab SDMA officially established.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2008 – Doaba Floods</h3>
        <p>
            • Overflow of Beas & Sutlej.<br>
            • Crops worth hundreds of crores destroyed.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2010 – Cloudburst Floods</h3>
        <p>
            • Intense cloudbursts triggered flash floods in northern districts.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2014 – Kashmir Flood Support</h3>
        <p>
            • Punjab deployed rescue teams to help J&K.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2019 – Ropar & Ludhiana Floods</h3>
        <p>
            • Sudden Bhakra dam discharge caused flooding.<br>
            • Dam communication protocols updated.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2020 – COVID-19 Disaster</h3>
        <p>
            • SDMA coordinated hospitals, oxygen, containment areas.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="year-block">
        <h3>2023 – Flash Floods</h3>
        <p>
            • Overflow of seasonal rivers in Hoshiarpur & Gurdaspur.<br>
            • NDRF & SDRF deployed.
        </p>
    </div>

    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <p>
        Punjab's journey from reactive relief to advanced disaster preparedness highlights its commitment to early warnings, flood forecasting, and multi-hazard planning.
